Alternatively, you can use integers (1, 0, -1) as flags in lieu of writing out cv2.IMREAD_COLOR, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE, etc.

Numpy and OpenCV¶

With OpenCV, we work with large numpy arrays.

  • For color images, they are 3 dimensional arrays.
  • And grayscale images, they are 2 dimensional.
In [6]:
print('Color image\n-------\nImage shape: {}\ntype: {}\nData type: {}\nDimensions: {}'
      .format(img.shape, type(img), img.dtype, img.ndim)
     )

Color image
-------
Image shape: (512, 512, 3)
type: <class 'numpy.ndarray'>
Data type: uint8
Dimensions: 3
In [7]:
print('Grayscale image\n-------\nImage shape: {}\ntype: {}\nData type: {}\nDimensions: {}'
      .format(img_grey.shape, type(img_grey), img_grey.dtype, img_grey.ndim)
     )

Grayscale image
-------
Image shape: (512, 512)
type: <class 'numpy.ndarray'>
Data type: uint8
Dimensions: 2

Cropping images¶

Okay, let's examine a small section of the image (region of interest (ROI)). Selecting the eye of the lenna.png.

For our grayscaled image,

  • img_gray[0,0] = top-left pixel intensity value

For the color image,

  • img[0,0,0] = top-left pixel value in our Blue channel (we'll discuss this below)

Color format¶

BGR –> Blue intensity, Green intensity, and Red intensity

In [11]:
# splitting the color channels
b, g, r = cv2.split(img)
In [12]:
# display color channels
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(6, 6), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax = axes.ravel()

ax[0].set_title("Blue Channel")
ax[0].imshow(b, cmap=plt.cm.Blues, interpolation = "nearest")

ax[1].set_title("Green Channel")
ax[1].imshow(g, cmap=plt.cm.Greens, interpolation = "nearest")

ax[2].set_title("Red Channel")
ax[2].imshow(r, cmap=plt.cm.Reds, interpolation = "nearest")

for a in ax:
    a.set_axis_off()

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [13]:
# recombine separated channels
recombined = cv2.merge((b, g, r))

# Recombine separated channels
plt.title("Recombined channels")
plt.imshow(recombined[...,::-1], interpolation = "nearest")
plt.show()

Converting between color format¶

The keen-eyed may have noticed that when plotting with matplotlib above, we reindexed our color image before plotting img[...,::-1]. OpenCV loads images in BGR mode, however, matplotlib and other software use RGB. Therefore, here, we reordered the image dimensions (the color channels) to reflect appear correctly.

In [14]:
# convert to rgb
img_rgb = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
In [15]:
# display original color and BGR converted image
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(8, 3), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax = axes.ravel()

ax[0].set_title("BGR")
ax[0].imshow(img, interpolation = "nearest")

ax[1].set_title("Reversed channels")
ax[1].imshow(img[...,::-1], interpolation = "nearest")

ax[2].set_title("BGR –> RGB")
ax[2].imshow(img_rgb, interpolation = "nearest")

for a in ax:
    a.set_axis_off()

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Image transformations¶

Basic geometric manipulation of our grayscale image. Rotations happen around top-left corner.

In [54]:
# basic rotation
img_rot1 = cv2.rotate(img_grey, cv2.ROTATE_90_CLOCKWISE)
img_rot2 = cv2.rotate(img_grey, cv2.ROTATE_180)
img_rot3 = cv2.rotate(img_grey, cv2.ROTATE_90_COUNTERCLOCKWISE)

# display original color and BGR converted image
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(12, 3), sharex=True, sharey=True)
ax = axes.ravel()

ax[0].set_title("Original color image")
ax[0].imshow(img_grey, cmap = plt.cm.gray, interpolation = "nearest")

ax[1].set_title("90° clockwise")
ax[1].imshow(img_rot1, cmap = plt.cm.gray, interpolation = "nearest")

ax[2].set_title("180° rotation")
ax[2].imshow(img_rot2, cmap = plt.cm.gray, interpolation = "nearest")

ax[3].set_title("90° counterclockwise rotation")
ax[3].imshow(img_rot3, cmap = plt.cm.gray, interpolation = "nearest")

for a in ax:
    a.set_axis_off()

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Rotation with Matrix transformation¶

Similarly, you can do with matrices. The function getRotationMatrix2D() takes a point to rotate the image around (here we're using the center of the image), angle in degree, and scale.

In [38]:
M1 = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D((img_grey.shape[0]/2 , img_grey.shape[1]/ 2), 90, 1)
print('This is a rotation matrix:\n{}'.format(M1))

This is a rotation matrix:
[[ 6.12323400e-17  1.00000000e+00 -2.84217094e-14]
 [-1.00000000e+00  6.12323400e-17  5.12000000e+02]]
In [61]:
rotations = [0, -90, 180, 90]
titles = ["Original color image", "90° clockwise", "180° rotation", "90° counterclockwise"]
In [104]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=len(rotations), figsize=(10,10), sharex='all', sharey='all')

for idx, (rotation, title) in enumerate(zip(rotations, titles)):
    M = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D((img_grey.shape[0] / 2 , img_grey.shape[1] / 2), rotation, 1)
    img_rotated = cv2.warpAffine(img_grey, M, (img_grey.shape[0], img_grey.shape[1]))
    axes[idx].set_title(title)
    axes[idx].imshow(img_rotated, cmap = plt.cm.gray, interpolation = "nearest")

Other transformations¶

In [102]:
# translation

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=len(rotations), figsize=(10,10), sharex='all', sharey='all')

for idx in range(4):
    M  = np.array([[1,0],[0,1]])
    trl = np.array([[20],[20]]) * idx
    M = np.c_[M, trl].astype(np.float64)
    img_rotated = cv2.warpAffine(img_grey, M, (img_grey.shape[0], img_grey.shape[1]))
    title = '{}: {}'.format('new origin', str(trl.flatten()))
    axes[idx].set_title(title)
    axes[idx].imshow(img_rotated, cmap = plt.cm.gray, interpolation = "nearest")
